@realmoney Today's strong trading sessions is the antithesis of yesterday's weak trading session. We continue in a choppy and range bound market - as such, Mr. Market seems to be in the no memory from day to day mode. As we move into next year and closer to the November

election I expect the market to get even more unpredictable and volatile as it seems, increasingly, that in our country everything is now about politics and little about policy. That's not a good thing in a mature market and long in the tooth economic recovery - and in which the

Fed has done just about all it can do (as the availability and cost of capital is not restricting growth). The markets this year have been buoyed by rising valuations but with only very limited profit growth we are in a risky spot in an interconnected global economy operating

at a record low level of cooperation and coordination. We are simply not as safe as citizens and investors as the markets seem to presume. I plan to reshort strength @tomkeene @NorthmanTrader @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @Sarge986 @jimcramer @riskreversal @guyadami @terranovajoe

These guys make it look so easy, Josh.

As we both know there are many ways to deliver superior investing and trading performance. I try to be adaptive. And this sort of market - choppy and artificial with little predictability - fits my style of finding stocks, sectors and Indices trading at variance with my calcu

lation of "fair market value." I believe truth is seen in cash flows and fundies and that untruth is seen and produced by passive strategies and products (ETFs, risk parity, etc.) that artificially impact prices. My approach is to embrace these factors the best I can.
Horses for courses my friend! You might be inactive for quit awhile!

Markets are complex and dynamic. They often change complexion. Either we adapt to and utilize the change to our advantage or traders wait for the market that is suitable to their strategy. I prefer the former (esp with such big swings great for opportunistic traders).

Rather than build false commentary and silly narratives explaining the daily or hourly market swings I would respectfully suggest: 1. Saying "I Dont Know" why the markets are moving 2. Saying the machines and algos are catching on to a very short term trend. 3. Repeat #1

@realmoney Oct 09, 2019 | 10:57 AM EDT DOUG KASS Chasing Price Momentum in Choppy Markets Will Just Chop You Up * I am trying to capture opportunities based on news items and artificial price moves * In choppy markets, chasing price momentum will just chop you up
Now I will describe what I am not doing. I am not following the selling lower (by shorting) or following the buying higher (by going long) as many price momentum based traders are.

Moves in "newsy" markets (both up and down) are exaggerated by today's dominant investors (ETFs and Quant Strategies like Risk Parity). These products reduce natural price discovery, are artificial and provide entry points to do just the opposite of selling lower and buying
higher. Buy low, sell high -- more than ever. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @michaelsantoli @carlquintanilla @Sarge986
Honestly Rev, to me Mr Market is very often a pain in the ass to trade!

Embrace Volatility and Use It To Your Advantage on @realmoney realmoney.thestreet.com/doug…

My opener @realmoney explains how I try to use volatility to my advantage. I personally think this is the best trading market in years. I can only address how I embrace vol. My view is that rather than shy away from markets,

one should consider how the wild swing in prices can help deliver excess returns in both investing and trading. A changing mkt complexion is nothing new - happens with frequency and adapting to change can be rewarding. As my horse trainer used to say, "Horses for courses."
It sure as hell is!
That is not what I am suggesting at all! I am saying both traders and investors should consider embracing the uncertainty of the markets.
